(681, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'France’s economy recently made the headlines in global financial news outlets as severely underperforming and plagued with a scarcity of small to medium enterprise investor appetite since the European debt crisis of 2010. Despite the fact that the French government implemented a drove of policies favorable towards business owners and shareholders, the memory of <a href="http://www.cnbc.com/id/102077802">2013’s Standard &amp; Poor’s downgrade</a> of the economy still sears many global investors’ impression of Eurozone’s second largest market.\r\n\r\nThanks to recent moves in crowdfunding-related regulation and the success of the practice as a means to capital raise, many major asset managers and institutional investors have explored ways to invest and support the most successful crowdfunding platforms available. This in order to enhance their price-discovery and due-diligence methodology. Thus on April 16<sup>th</sup>, French equity crowdfunding platform <a href="https://www.smartangels.fr/">SmartAngels</a> and the French arm of the global insurer <a href="https://allianz.smartangels.fr/">Allianz</a> announced the launch of a €10M crowdfunding investment fund to back promising start-ups in the French market.\r\n\r\nThe joint partnership between the two investors allows French investors to support equity crowdfunded investments for startups needing between €15,000 and €1,000,000. The platform makes it possible for investors to choose potential ventures to back according to sectors, geography, stage of growth, and degree of innovativeness in their business model. Individuals who opt to use the platform get to build their portfolios along their criteria in the offered list of pre-selected and pre-analyzed ventures. The listed ventures are vetted by Allianz and SmartAngels’ business analysts during the due-diligence process, as well as continuously as the selected ventures begin to gather public attention and successful crowdfunding streaks.\r\n\r\nA key element of this innovation in French capital-raising tools is that it allows private investors, and non-accredited investors, to invest in startups and SMEs (Small and Medium Enterprises) equities traditionally restricted to higher net-worth individuals. Venture Capital investment typically returns up to 11 times the initial invested amount as seed stage companies grow to be acquired by strategic investors or to their own initial public offering stage. This therefore presents a much more profitable set of investment opportunities for private investors compared to other available asset classes such as plain equities, ETFs, and other indexed and mutual fund instruments which hover between 0.05 and 2%.\r\n\r\nA key insurance-related element of Allianz’s and SmartAngels’ partnership is that their proposed platform qualifies for French Capital Markets Authorities supervision (<a href="http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amf-france.org%2F&amp;ei=rQ0xVZKgPMmsyASi3YDgCw&amp;usg=AFQjCNFIRNbRH5VikL7CGM-mE2R8WOASwQ&amp;sig2=7Mk6qKGcyxAMpvfbAyPWUQ&amp;bvm=bv.91071109,d.aWw">Autorité des Marchés Financiers</a>). This means that third party agents are in charge of intermediation during the exchange of equities for funds and obtained capital gains, or losses, and the invested companies’ operating accounts. The platform therefore acts as a neutral third party, able to fend off management risk and moral hazard that comes with investee companies managing the flows of shareholder invested capital without sufficient disclosure.\r\n\r\nWhat’s more participant private investors get to <a href="https://www.smartangels.fr/welcome/register?allianz=1">have access to audited financials</a> of all startups they chose to invest in, the overwhelming majority of which are under constant monitoring by crowdfunding platform-related analysts. There is thus an effective agreement between investors, shareholders, platform managers, and investee companies, during the exchange of value between all parties.\r\n\r\nThe essential innovation entailed by Allianz’ involvement in equity crowdfunding lies in the fact that participating investors are insured as investors. They also have the option to co-invest alongside a major institutional investor in their quest for capital gains. Thus, as soon as investors decide to invest in a company, they have the option to have Allianz match, and therefore double, their investment as co-investors.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Allianz gets to exercise its expertise as an insurance company, insuring investors’ investments in a wide variety of occasions. Allianz give participating private investors the option to gain downside protection for the positions they opt to take, with the option to have the insurance firm purchase back various equities previously committed to troubled listing companies. For example: if an investor commits €2,000 and later finds out about misrepresentations, inaccuracies in financial documents, or other non-performance on a given startup’s business case to shareholders<a href="https://allianz.smartangels.fr/">, Allianz commits itself to pay back</a> the invested amount back.\r\n\r\nThis new partnership allows Allianz’s customers to invest and gain from the insurance company’s co-investment in chosen startups, for up to €50,000, per individual, per company. Crowdfunding insider sees this move as particularly useful since it leaves the ultimate success or failure of a given startup’s success in crowdfunding to the <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/04/66241-smartangels-and-global-insurer-allianz-launch-e10-m-crowdfunding-investment-fund/">mass purchasing public</a>. Which allows prospective venture capital firms and institutional investors looking to support listing companies beyond the current €1.000.000 limit to get real-time feedback as to a given venture’s future promise as an initial public offering prospect. This explains why another Venture Capital partner of Allianz’s in this venture, <a href="https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/idinvest-partners">IDInvest</a>, has committed itself ahead of time to select the most successful crowdfunding campaign startups for further rounds of capital raising as part of its own due-diligence and deal pipeline vetting process.\r\n\r\nAt the time of writing, SmartAngels has collected more than €11,000,000 in 2012 alone, funding more than 20 startups and listing companies with Allianz’s help. This essential partnership between a key risk management player in European capital markets and some of savviest and most selective players in the venture investing game is sure to boost French SME finance in the coming quarters.', 'Insurance Company Allianz Pairs up with France’s Smart Anglels to Back €10M in Equity Crowdfunding', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=681', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(682, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'The aftermath of the 2007 financial crisis left many an observer desperate to see credible and effective steps taken by G20 Government to rein in financial exuberance and global banking risk. As a result, the Obama administration, alongside its G20 partners announced sweeping new standards to global banking. Inside the world’s biggest capital market, the United States, the Securities and Exchange Commission met the Dodd-Frank Act, named after two senators, a regulation designed to de-risk the American financial system and get rid of too-big-to-fail.\r\n\r\nOn a global scale, the G20 agreed to delegate a level of regulatory guidance to the <a href="http://www.financialstabilityboard.org/">Financial Stability Board</a>, headed by the soundest central banker in the world at the time: the Canadian Mark Carney. Almost a decade after the announced reforms, Securities and Exchanges Commission Commissioner Gallagher <a href="https://www.scribd.com/document_downloads/262049103?extension=pdf&amp;from=embed&amp;source=embed">spoke at a Harvard Law School</a> symposium on international financial stability. He decried the fact that both announced solutions to the 2007 crisis are more politics than they constitute sound prudential norms in banking, they prevent small business from accessing much needed capital.\r\n\r\nThe Commissioner argues that the bureaucratic institutional structure that comes with the Financial Stability Board’s regulatory authority puts pressures on domestic regulators worldwide. This pressure, he suggests, incentivizes individual State regulators to apply an essentially political set of rules with little oversight. Often devoid of any functional consideration for what works in sound banking, under the threat of direct pressure by their respective Heads of State. According to him, these rules outlined mainly in the Dodd-Frank Act, are essentially a manifesto that aims to remove the concept of risk from the mainstream of American banking, and seeks to change the business model of banking.\r\n\r\nThis political process, the commissioner suggest, is evident in the procedures and arguments used to push the Dodd-Frank Act’s regulation forward. Gallagher makes the argument that the Republican Party’s majority in Congress presented American Financial regulators with an unprecedented opportunity to implement a decade-long list of pent-up legislative “wish list” for a coterie of domestic industries. The resulting large two thousand pages long Act, he argues, full of vaguely defined socially and politically motivated principles in financial rule-making made it almost impossible for American regulatory agencies to implement.\r\n\r\nDomestically, he suggests, Dodd Drank regulates the banking system unilaterally with very little consideration for competitiveness and the changed global financial landscape and its effect on bank performance in America. This point is of note since the process of financial regulation has traditionally been more consultative and consensus-driven since the earliest days of the country’s regulatory history. There is little team work involved, and a political set of rules more intended to appeal to populist audiences than to effective financial-operational observers, is having counter-productive effects on American finance since 2007.\r\n\r\nMore specifically, the Commissioner argues that since 2007, the desire of regulators and politicians to harmonize regulation, hoping for a uniform and stringent set of banking rules, is now a top-down forced implementation of one-size-fits-all rules. These rules are notably oblivious to the finer principle that previously governed balancing investor protection and efficient, effective, banking system operations.  His view is that this new set of appending regulations is leading to a lopsided set of rules that are having an adverse effect on American banking.\r\n\r\nThis adverse effect on American banking consists of lowering competitiveness of American banks. The Dodd-Frank Rules put forward the most stringent rules and principles possible with an eye to rein in risk, with no additional support for investor protection, just as they restrain the banking sector’s ability to cost-efficiently led to a credit-starved domestic economy.\r\n\r\nOne other side effect of the deeply political and operationally obtuse nature of Dodd-Frank is that American regulators have engaged in a seven years long goose chase for existing institutions that meet its new Systemically Important Financial Institutions label. These raise the cost of banking and add to required reserve requirements, without having any complementary effect in instilling confidence or effective reining in the riskiest elements of asset management. These side-effects not-withstanding, the Dodd-Frank Act effectively centralizes command and control of the asset management industry through its main creation: the Financial Stability Oversight Council, or FSOC.\r\n\r\nOn a global scale, this political move by regulators, backed by the G20 Heads of States, has given the Financial Stability Board to overtake domestic institutions in the management of a very different set of regulatory landscapes. As a result of announced rules, and sufficient pressure applied by FSB governors, all financial markets, regardless of local specificities, are now governed by the same set of expensive and ineffective prudential rules.\r\n\r\nThis one size-fits-all approach explains why, after domestically tagging many specifically American players as SIFIs, the FSB is at a loss to deem any other jurisdiction’s banks as G-SIFIs, Global Systemically Significant Financial Institutions. This new regulatory dynamic is benefiting Chinese financial sector firms, for example, since the onerous standards applied allows them to accept a greater amount of risk as “smaller” or “less significant” institutions. What’s more many other markets, in the Middle East, Asia, and other parts of the developing world are considering avoiding the FSB’s coercive authority because Dodd-Frank style global standards are proving impractical in a drove of markets.\r\n\r\nAt a time when United States and European financial institutions compete as providers of capital with Hong Kong, Singapore, Shanghai, the Dubai International Financial Center, it is high time that applicable regulation acquired a greater eye for competitiveness. The alternative is irrelevance.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Financial Stability Board & Dodd-Frank More Politics than Sound Regulation   ', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=682', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(683, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'On April 13<sup>th</sup>, 2015, <a href="http://www.stantive.com/">Stantive Technologies</a> announced that it has successfully joined the <a href="http://www.salesforce.com/ca/">Salesforce</a> Partner Program for Independent Software Vendors program after a competitive selection process. Stantive Technologies Group is a Canadian-based technology company that specializes in expert-delivery of enterprise portals, social intranets, corporate websites featuring <a href="http://www.appexchange.com/orchestracms">OrchestraCMS</a>, an industry-renowned content-management system that was developed natively on the Salesforces1 Platform. Stantive’s successful platform allows for a high level of effortless cross-integration and collaborative tools and database creation that results in a deep level collaboration, content-driven digital channels and value-chains, along with a sophisticated ease of customization for varied business uses.\r\n\r\nUsing their innovative approach, this technology group is changing the game of content management, along with its industry. It does so by empowering institutions, their stakeholders, management, and whole organizations to properly administer, create, and publish internet or “web” content in a seamlessly integrated and dynamic way. It accomplishes this in a fraction of time and corporate resources typically required by more traditional and mainstream CMS (Content Management Systems).\r\n\r\nThis integration therefore made the most sense given the synergies to be had between both platforms, one being an expert <a href="http://www.salesforce.com/ca/#more">CMS</a> integration solution, and the other having honed its expertise on sales management using the latest cloud technologies. Stantive Technologies is sure to take advantage of Salesforces’ established expertise in simultaneously managing business processes, people, and innovative technological solutions in order to help client companies and partners acquire and maintain and expending customer base.\r\n\r\nWhat’s more Salesforces’ processes efficiently build-in data and performance tools to enhance and empower its related sales teams. They accomplish this largely though their <a href="http://www.salesforce.com/ca/sales-cloud/overview/?d=70130000000tMoN&amp;internal=true">Sales Perfomance Accelerator</a>. Stantive Technologies can now freely explore synergistic opportunities to further explore Salesforces’ cutting edge tracking technology along with its complex integrated mobile and interactive workplace all on the same dashboard, regardless of where individual sales agents are located.\r\n\r\nWhat’s more, Salesforces and Stantive Technologies will both be able to collaborate in providing a wide variety of <a href="http://www.salesforce.com/ca/#more">CRM Solutions</a> to their expanding client-base. Their clients will benefit from a better sales, marketing, and customer support management campaigns as they further exceed their bottom-line and set quarterly sales objectives.\r\n\r\nThis will be possible thanks to both providers’ focus on CRM-related solutions in Sales and marketing, activity management, and customer service support management. All of these are made even more helpful by fully taking advantage of the disruptive set of cloud-computing technologies they now feature. This additional tool will enhance Stantive Technologies as a Vendor Partner, to successfully reduce operational costs while maintaining a principal and central base of infrastructure and code-base at the very heart of this new model.\r\n\r\nIn particular, Stantive’s Orchestra CMS will further help Salesforce’s many users take even greater advantage of digital content online to fulfill the business priorities and objectives of their client-base’s mobile and online web experiences. There is already a long history of partnership between Stantive Technologies and Salesforce, which started in 2003; both should find it uniquely easy to expand the range of their offerings to an ever expanding set of Fortune 1000 companies worldwide. Salesforce is equally thrilled of the partnership as is evident in the <a href="http://linkis.com/www.stantive.com/Uc4R6">partners’ press release of the announcement</a><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB4QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fin%2Fronhuddleston1&amp;ei=Ei4xVZnnNIuKyAT2-IGgAg&amp;usg=AFQjCNGho88BveOkHqp-pbSDfLaxLmfb9w&amp;sig2=YMcDmFeuK4OgMqSXo-lb7w&amp;bvm=bv.91071109,d.aWw">. Ron Huddleston,</a> Senior Vice President, ISV &amp; Channel, at Salesforce explains that “Stantive is an important partner and builds upon the business value being delivered with our platform”.\r\n\r\nFor Stantive Technology’s part, its Founder and CEO, Doug Irvin, <a href="http://linkis.com/www.stantive.com/Uc4R6">expresses his enthusiasm</a>: “We’re excited to officially join the Salesforce Partner Program for Independent Software Vendors and help companies transform the way they connect with customers, partners and employees”.  This is evidently a welcome step forward in expanding Ontario’s available, cost-efficient, and cutting edge set of small-business offerings.', 'Salesforce’s Independent Software Vendors Program Welcomes Stantive Technologies Group', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=683', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(687, 10, '2015-04-26 16:22:21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX like to suggest that equity crowdfunding is a thoroughly global phenomenon – a novel mode of generating finances and consumer involvement that’s taking the world by storm. In this series, therefore, we set about showing you what we have been saying all along: the opportunities are endless, and in many cases, they are right in your backyard!\r\n\r\nLet’s take a closer look at what’s going on in terms of equity crowdfunding in Canada, and what’s to come in 2015:\r\n\r\n1) Accessibility to significant funds is going up! Specifically, last year saw a record-breaking campaign raise <a href="http://www.itbusiness.ca/blog/a-fearless-look-ahead-at-crowdfunding-in-canada-for-2015/53033">$1.3 million</a> – more than sixty percent more than the top 2013 campaign had managed to come up with ($817 000). As such, it seems that equity crowdfunding is generating more and more promise where access to significant funding is concerned – in other words, equity crowdfunding has grown to a level where it can be regarded as a fundraising tool worthy of serious consideration.\r\n\r\n2) <a href="http://www.itbusiness.ca/blog/a-fearless-look-ahead-at-crowdfunding-in-canada-for-2015/53033">Daryl Hatton</a>, CEO of platform FundRazr, says it isn’t just the quantity of readily accessible funding that’s escalating in the Canadian equity crowdfunding sphere – equity crowdfunding is also seeing increased awareness from the general populace! Specifically, Hatton says that 2014 saw a significant component of the population “starting or participating in crowdfunding campaigns”; <em>itbusiness.ca</em>’s <a href="http://www.itbusiness.ca/blog/a-fearless-look-ahead-at-crowdfunding-in-canada-for-2015/53033">Bret Conkin</a> concurs, suggesting that equity crowdfunding “hit the mainstream” in Canada in 2014 – things are just getting started, so now’s a great time to get accustomed to the equity crowdfunding climate in Canada!\r\n\r\n3) The first <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/2015-canadian-crowdfunding-summit-early-bird-registration-now-open/">Canadian Crowdfunding Summit</a> happened this March 2015! This platform for discussion was a very important one to put in place, as it will allow for increased awareness and education where equity crowdfunding is concerned; a lack of awareness and education was cited by experts as one of the two leading issues for Canadian equity crowdfunding in 2015.\r\n\r\n4) Experts note that, while the market for equity crowdfunding will continue to emerge, it will do so more slowly than would be desired by its admirers, particularly because regulators, at the moment, need to implement a set of fraud-prevention mechanisms. 2015, hopefully, will see the finalization of certain regulations in Canada, as well as in the U.S., according to <a href="http://www.itbusiness.ca/blog/a-fearless-look-ahead-at-crowdfunding-in-canada-for-2015/53033">Gil Michel-Garcia</a> of WAFU. Suzanne Paschal of Indie Ink Publishing notes that, as much as regulations are necessary, they may hold off optimal market growth until 2016.\r\n\r\nConclusively, then? Canadian equity crowdfunding is emerging, but it may still have a couple of years to go before it truly booms!\r\n\r\nIn anticipation of a time when equity crowdfunding truly will be the next big thing for nearly everyone, we feel it’s wise to get ahead, and learn about existing equity crowdfunding initiatives, portals, and people in Canada.\r\n\r\nOne key group to be aware of is the National Crowdfunding Association of Canada (<a href="http://ncfacanada.org">NCFA</a>). A cross-Canada non-profit, the NCFA seeks to get in touch with both social and investment crowdfunding stakeholders across the country, and keep them actively engaged. NCFA Canada also aims to provide you with the research, information, events, leadership, and networking you need to get involved in the crowdfunding industry in Canada. Finally, it aims to reach out internationally to enable crowdfunding leaders around the world to stay in touch.\r\n\r\nWhat can you gain from the NCFA?\r\n\r\na) A solid crowdfunding education! NCFA’s website has a <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/book-library/">book library</a> and <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/video-library/">video library</a> replete with info. about equity crowdfunding, as well as two courses – <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/crowdfunding/">Crowdfunding 101</a> and <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/crowdfunding-is-essential-for-sme-innovation-and-job-creation/">Crowdfunding 201</a> – that can teach you everything you need to know about this emerging market. Check them out here!\r\n\r\nb) A well of recently-published research concerning equity crowdfunding at both the Canadian and the international levels!\r\n\r\nc) Participation in exciting events, which provide further opportunities to learn about equity crowdfunding, and chances to network with other entrepreneurs interested in this novel space! In fact, the NCFA’s got a <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/business-innovation-summit-2015-connect-collaborate-and-innovate-together/">Business Innovation Summit</a> coming up later this week, on the twenty-eighth and the twenty-ninth of April; try to come out! If you can’t, there’s always the <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/toronto-event-june-2-money-forum-2015/">Money Forum</a> on the second of June!\r\n\r\nd) Access to a <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/canadian-crowdfunding-directory/">directory</a> of other Canadian crowdfunding organizations, portals, and people! KoreConX can be of help when it comes to selecting a platform, but NCFA’s got the definitive list, for the moment!\r\n\r\ne) Information about currently active equity <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/canadian-campaigns/">crowdfunding campaigns</a> that you can invest in!\r\n\r\nf) All the latest info. concerning equity crowdfunding <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/provincial-regulations-and-resources/">rules and regulations</a>, specific to Canada, as well as specific information for <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/for-investors/">investors</a> and <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/for-entrepreneurs/">entrepreneurs</a>!\r\n\r\nAll in all, then, know that equity crowdfunding is quickly hitting the big-time in Canada, and that now’s as good a time as ever to find out more about this exciting emerging market!', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Canadian Focus', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-04-26 16:22:21', '2015-04-26 16:22:21', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=687', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(688, 10, '2015-05-11 18:55:02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '[caption id="attachment_738" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/USA.png"><img class="wp-image-738 size-medium" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/USA-300x250.png" alt="USA Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> USA Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nContinuing on with our “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” series (you can read our Canadian articles here), let’s take a closer look at what’s happening in the United States of America – home to one of, arguably, the biggest potential markets where equity crowdfunding is concerned!\r\n\r\n1) In 2013, equity crowdfunding was <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jorge-newbery/crowdfunding-is-growing-u_b_4980206.html">not yet legal</a> in the USA. By March 2014, however, close to 1000 crowdfunding sites existed in the space! Clearly, then, equity crowdfunding saw incredible growth in the USA market, just as it has in several others.\r\n\r\n2) While this space was initially restricted, in the minds of consumers, to donation-based and reward-based platforms like Kickstarter and Indiegogo, the Jumpstart Our Business Startups (<a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FJumpstart_Our_Business_Startups_Act&amp;ei=org7VfGEONeHsQSF6IHgAQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNEUJKvAEsvtEVdLGS7-YY9uMa6uBA&amp;sig2=SW6EqlZ7xDtGmMR59WMNcA&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">JOBS</a>) Act has resulted in an expanded definition of equity crowdfunding. Now, anyone can join in! Small businesses and start-ups, according to this legislation, can publicly seek funding, and individuals can become investors in their offerings!\r\n\r\n3) Equity crowdfunding is expected to grow in the USA in 2015! In fact, it seems that, according to the Tabb Group, the market may well hit <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jorge-newbery/crowdfunding-is-growing-u_b_4980206.html">$17 billion</a> after having been forecasted to hit $10 billion in 2014! A lot of this funding is coming from angel investors, who are expected to invest anywhere between $30 billion and $50 billion in the market in 2015!\r\n\r\nSpecifically, where 2015 is concerned, a few trends are expected:\r\n\r\na) Things will move slowly! We’re still in the process of finalizing crowdfunding legislation in the USA, as the relevant body – the SEC – has delayed open distribution of regulation in order to figure out if it’s hit a balance between too much and too little legislation. It seems that, just as is the case in Canada, regulation has yet to be conclusively established for the United States.\r\n\r\nb) Because of how many platforms are already active, the number of novel crowdfunding platforms that attain competitive status will be comparatively lower than before, while existing platforms will consolidate their work in order to satisfactorily build trust with investors.\r\n\r\nc) The regulations surrounding crowdfunding will be so important in light of the strength that this industry has accumulated that regulation crowdfunding may well become important in the next presidential election. It appears that nearly everyone, Republicans and Democrats behind, will stand behind the business, and this’ll foster increased protection against investor fraud, which will in turn advance the industry!\r\n\r\nd) Major venture capitalists may be more likely to take the concept seriously, given its exponential growth! Some think that such major venture capitalists as <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-drake/crowdfunding-grows-up-4-t_b_6398444.html">Blackstone</a> and <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-drake/crowdfunding-grows-up-4-t_b_6398444.html">Andreessen Horowitz</a> will be backing crowdfunding in 2015!\r\n\r\nClearly, then, just as was the case in Canada, the USA has its fair share of equity crowdfunding action, offering benefits for investors and entrepreneurs alike!\r\n\r\nIf you’re a USA start-up looking to gain more information about this particular line of funding, by the way, you may be interested in figuring out how, precisely, you can get involved in all this. The following websites can be of help in that:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="https://circleup.com/">CircleUp</a>: A US site with several success investment stories to its name, with allows investors to communicate directly with CEOs, possess access to all financials and diligence documents, work with both consumer and retail investors, and invest directly into companies of their choice! Entrepreneurs, on the other hand, have the benefits of working with partners like General Mills, P&amp;G, and SPINs via CircleUp’s connections, and can utilize innovative online tools to manage investor relations!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="https://angel.co/">AngelList</a>: Another US site, this one specifically for accredited investors: only accredit investors can invest, at the moment, while start-ups can utilize this site to raise equity or debt for their work! AngelList can also be utilize for recruitment and job-searching!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.earlyshares.com/">Early Shares</a>: A site that gives accredited US investors direct access to private opportunities in real estate and investment funds; thousands of investors, presumably, frequent the site, with potential for more than $200 million to be invested in the next twelve months! This site is particularly selective, accepting fewer than 5% of applicants!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese sites and many others are now open to investors and entrepreneurs working in the USA equity crowdfunding space; as such, now is a great time to get involved in this emerging market if you’re working in the States.', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: USA Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-around-world-usa-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:55:02', '2015-05-11 18:55:02', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=688', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(689, 10, '2015-05-11 18:52:07', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '“Crowdfunding has the capacity to galvanize innovation, create jobs, diversity economic activity, and contribute to the reduction of income inequality by improving access to affordable capital and bridging the gap between funding demand and capital supply for entrepreneurs and micro, small, and medium enterprises in Mexico.” – <em>Crowdfunding in Mexico: The Power of Digital Technologies to Transform Innovation, Entrepreneurship and Economic Exclusion [</em><a href="http://www.crowdsourcing.org/editorial/crowdfunding-in-mexico-the-power-of-digital-technologies-to-transform-innovation-entrepreneurship-and-economic-inclusion-report/31100"><em>report</em></a><em>]</em>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_734" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Mexico.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-734" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Mexico-300x250.png" alt="Mexican Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> Mexican Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nGiven that we recently discussed equity crowdfunding opportunities in both Canada and the USA, it would make sense to look at another North American country: namely, Mexico! Just south of the States, Mexico is actually a relatively reasonable candidate for an equity crowdfunding boom, what with its “bustling engineering and innovation community”, as <em>Forbes’s</em> <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">Chance Barnett</a> describes it, and an ecosystem “ripe for entrepreneurial growth”.\r\n\r\nAs early as 2012, Chance himself – the founder of Crowdfunder.com – was invited to speak to Mexican leaders about the impact that crowdfunding could have in Mexico. Inspired by the JOBS Act and Crowdfunder’s success, prominent Mexican business figures wanted to see how equity crowdfunding could function in their own locale. As of 2013, perhaps as a result of these conversations, Crowdfunder.mx was born, bringing access to crowdfunding capital to Mexican entrepreneurs, and generating a useful online network for Mexican investors, as well!\r\n\r\nSo, crowdfunding has definitely entered Mexico. But why can it succeed there?\r\n\r\n1) As noted, Mexico is ripe with entrepreneurial spirit! It is even Startup Weekend’s largest market outside of the US for startup culture, and sometimes, over <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">100 000</a> new engineers graduate in Mexico on an annual basis! Clearly, then, there are lots of opportunities to find innovative, investment-worthy projects in Mexico.\r\n\r\n2) It is specifically small business that drives the Mexican economy: small and medium businesses (hereafter, SMBs) make up about <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">72%</a> of job creation in Mexico, and <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">52%</a> of its GDP! As such, given how well equity crowdfunding aligns with small and medium business ventures, there’s a chance that a lot can be done by equity crowdfunding within the country.\r\n\r\n3) While there are so many SMBs in Mexico, most of them fail – three out of four, in fact! Why? Largely because they cannot access the funds they need to succeed. Generating capital is a significant challenge in Mexico, but that’s precisely what equity crowdfunding is for. Chances are, if many equity crowdfunding platforms were to become predominant within the nation, the Mexican entrepreneurial economy would greatly benefit, and would thus, in turn, become more and more interested in using these funding options.\r\n\r\nAt present, then, it appears that the time is right to enter Mexico! Crowdfunder has done so with <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">Crowdfunder.mx</a>, and several leading platforms are following suite, seeing <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/chance-barnett/will-equity-crowdfunding-_b_4904534.html">rapid clustering outcomes</a> (<em>i.e.</em>, fast connection of entrepreneurs to investors) in places like Mexico, precisely because investors there are very interested in top deal flow, and entrepreneurs, in turn, lack investors at the Seed and Series A stages.\r\n\r\nHowever, the next step, as always, is another challenging one: increasing awareness of and education about crowdfunding. As a comparatively novel funding strategy, equity crowdfunding needs to become prominent in the eyes of Mexican entrepreneurs and investors.\r\n\r\nIn that vein, several novel initiatives have come to fruition: Crowdfunder.mx, firstly, has partnered with Mexican partners like Endeavor Mexico, Angel Ventures Mexico, Monterrey Tech, 500 Startups Mexico City, and others! These strategic partnerships will help the platform disseminate information about equity crowdfunding, which it hopes can breed a novel capital climate in the country. Further, educational seminars like <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">CROWDFUNDx</a> – a seminar series based on the successful TEDx model – have surfaced not solely in the US, but also in Mexico, targeting over ten cities (including Chihuahua, Ciudad Obregon, Guadalajara, Tijuana, Oaxaca, Mexico City, and Aguascalientes). With ever-increasing education, the Mexican equity crowdfunding ecosystem is expected to grow more and more!\r\n\r\nAt present, it’s important to note that, while Mexican crowdfunding is definitely existent, there’s little room for non-accredited investors. By the Mexican definition, an accredited investor is someone who makes roughly $160 000 USD, as opposed to the US $200 000 qualification for an accredit investor, however, so do keep that in mind, as well! Relatively few crowdfunding regulations are as yet established in Mexico, so though the country has been called the <a href="http://www.fomin.org/en-us/Home/News/PressReleases/ArtMID/3819/ArticleID/1100/First-study-about-crowdfunding-in-Mexico-positions-the-country-as-leader-in-Latin-America-.aspx">leader</a> in crowdfunding in Latin America, it will have to establish a legal framework to outline the activities permitted under equity crowdfunding in its locale.', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Mexican Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-around-world-mexican-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:52:07', '2015-05-11 18:52:07', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=689', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(690, 10, '2015-05-11 18:50:18', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Thus far, we’ve examined Canada, the USA, and Mexico in the context of equity crowdfunding, a novel form of generating capital that’s had a truly global outbreak in the last three or so years. At present, given that we have a good idea of how equity crowdfunding has opened up in North America in the recent past, let’s take a closer look at East Asia where this funding strategy is concerned; specifically, as could be expected, given its economic illustriousness, let’s commence with China!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_732" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/China.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-732" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/China-300x250.png" alt="Chinese Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> Chinese Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo, what’s the state of equity crowdfunding in China? It’s so compelling, in fact, that <em>Forbes</em>’s <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/">Conor Roche</a> believes China could “kick off a new wave in equity crowdfunding that might even leave the European and US-based philanthropic and rewards-based crowdfunding movements in the dust”! In short, while US startups have thus far dominated the crowdfunding space where art and design is concerned, Roche – who works in Shanghai, and co-leads a CultureCrowd.co.uk research project into crowdfunding – says that China has immense potential where funding “serious entrepreneurial projects” is concerned!\r\n\r\nAt present, China also has about thirty crowdfunding sites. The largest-grossing project thus far has been on a site called Demohour; it raised $260 000 (131% of its target) from 3596 users for a certain movie. On this basis, and on the basis of a look at China’s economic ecosystem, the World Bank has presumably suggested that Chinese crowdfunding could become a <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/2/">$50 billion</a> industry by just 2025! We certainly are poised for rapid growth.\r\n\r\nThis is probably exacerbated by the fact that there is elevated respect for tech incubators, startups, and design-oriented businesses in China, at the moment – both local and regional governments are supporting these kinds of initiatives. Further, creative industries make up ten percent of the Chinese community; China has a novel focus on the arts and <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/2/">museum-building</a> that Roche hopes can be nurtured by equity crowdfunding. Additionally, there is the fact that the Chinese government as a whole is trying to eliminate US-based tech products from its people’s options; by banning the likes of Twitter and Facebook, China has helped create copied versions of these products, which it hopes can gain traction even outside of China at some point.\r\n\r\nIt’s important to note, however, that despite all this buzz, equity crowdfunding is not as yet well-regulated in China – until recently, in fact, it was illegal. There’s been an exception to this, to be sure: China tried a <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/2/">short experiment</a> that allowed users to invest up to RMB 100 up to two times on certain cultural projects, expecting an annual return of seven percent on the original investment. And <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/2/">Roche himself</a> hopes to launch an equity crowdfunding platform in the Shanghai Free Trade Zone – a region with comparatively relaxed regulations!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://techcrunch.com/2013/05/14/equity-crowd-funding-site-seedasia-launches/">SeedAsia</a>, as well, an equity crowdfunding site based in China, launched in 2013. Somewhat like Kickstarter and part private investment, the SeedAsia platform allows startups to offer between $50 000 and $1.5 million in equity to investors, and potential investors are applied and screened, with a minimum investment commitment of $2000 per member. SeedAsia was actually the first crowdfunding site to launch in the region, so it’s a considerably important name to keep in mind when considering Chinese crowdfunding!\r\n\r\nIf you’ve interest in exploring the crowdfunding space in China, it may well be productive to consider visiting the following top Chinese crowdfunding sites:\r\n\r\n1) Demohour: Launched in 2011, Demohour has received millions of dollars from such names as Intel Capital, and is most similar to Kickstarter.\r\n\r\n2) AngelCrunch: One of the largest equity crowdfunding platforms, this site was also founded in 2011, and is effectively the equivalent of AngelList, which we discussed in our USA feature!\r\n\r\n3) Dreamore: Largely a site for creative projects, taking advantage of the country’s drive towards such things, Dreamore is comparatively recent, with the domain’s being updated to its present form in 2013.\r\n\r\nOther sites include Fundator (another 2013 launch), Musikid (geared specifically at music projects), CTQuan (another platform trying to mimic AngelList), and ZhongChou (another platform for creative projects). Alibaba’s Yue Bao is another online investment fund! Most recently, in fact, in April 2015, <a href="http://www.marketwatch.com/story/a-new-player-emerges-in-equity-crowdfunding-in-china-2015-04-01">JD.com</a> – a Beijing-based e-commerce site – also set up a crowdfunding platform! The site has launched with eleven companies raising funds, and its investors have to meet a certain standard. JD.com is also trying its hand at offering educational resources similar to those that NCFA Canada puts forth (<em>i.e.</em>, support and training for startups).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Chinese Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-around-world-chinese-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:50:18', '2015-05-11 18:50:18', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=690', 0, 'post', '', 0);
