(726, 10, '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In our last two articles, we centered on the exempt market dealer (EMD) designation, and discussed both the process inherent to becoming an EMD, and the benefits that working with an EMD may bring to essentially any company.\r\n\r\nIf you read “How do you become an exempt market dealer?”, you’ll know that registering an EMD requires the participation of one or more dealing representatives, one ultimate designated person, and one chief compliance officer (CCO). While the dealing representatives act as dealers or underwriters with respect to securities, the ultimate designated person supervises the activities of the firm, ensuring compliance with securities legislation by the firm as a whole and by each individual, and also promotes compliance by the firm and its individuals. The chief compliance officer (CCO), meanwhile, is responsible for most of the executive work involved in running an EMD. He or she establishes and maintains policies and procedures for assessing compliance with securities legislation (both by the firm and by the individuals acting on its behalf), monitors compliance on a routine basis, and reports to the ultimate designated person of the firm if any circumstances are in non-compliance with the relevant legislation. The chief compliance officer (CCO) is also responsible for an annual report to the firm’s board of directors that assesses compliance of the firm and its affiliated individuals.\r\n\r\nSo, who can be a chief compliance officer (CCO), and how can a person become one?\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The CCO must, firstly, be either an officer or partner of a registered firm, or its sole proprietor.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n	<li>Assuming this criterion is met, the potential CCO must then:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Pass the PDO Exam and the Canadian Securities Course Exam, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Pass the PDO Exam and the Exempt Market Products Exam, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Meet the requirements of a portfolio manager’s chief compliance officer, namely:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Earned a CFA Charter or professional designation as a lawyer, Chartered Accountant, Certified General Accountant, or Certified Management Accountant in some jurisdiction of Canada, a notary in Quebec, or the equivalent in a foreign jurisdiction, passed the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam, and gained thirty-six months of relevant securities experience while working at an investment dealer, a registered adviser, or an investment fund manager, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Earned a CFA Charter or professional designation as a lawyer, Chartered Accountant, Certified General Accountant, or Certified Management Accountant in some jurisdiction of Canada, a notary in Quebec, or the equivalent in a foreign jurisdiction, passed the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam, and provided professional services in the securities industry for thirty-six months and worked at a registered dealer, registered adviser, or investment fund manager for three months, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Pass the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam and have worked at an investment dealer or a registered adviser for five years, including for thirty-six months in a compliance capacity, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Pass the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam and have worked for five years at a Canadian financial institution in a compliance capacity pertaining to portfolio management and worked at a registered dealer or a registered adviser for twelve months, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Pass the PDO Exam and meet the requirements a portfolio manager’s advising representative, namely:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Earn a CFA Charter and have twelve months of relevant investment management experience in the thirty-six month period before applying for registration, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Receive a Canadian Investment Manager designation, have forty-eight months of relevant investment management experience, twelve months of which was in the thirty-six month period before applying for registration</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n	<li>If the relevant criteria are met, the potential CCO may register as a CCO by filling in <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/form_33-109f4.pdf">Form 33-109F4 (Individual Registration)</a>, and submitting it at either the National Registration Database (NRD) website in NRD format at <a href="http://www.nrd.ca">nrd.ca</a>, or, if relying on the temporary hardship exemption discussed in Section 5.1 of NI 31-102, in a different format to a principal regulator/SRO. If you are a potential CCO, and need help with what you should be doing when filling out this paperwork, contact your sponsoring firm, or a legal adviser who’s comfortable with securities law.</li>\r\n</ol>', 'What do you need to be a CCO for an EMD?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'need-cco-emd', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=726', 0, 'post', '', 0),
